Here's the approach: bypass `IFormFile` (which buffers in memory) and read the multipart body directly using `MultipartReader`.

**Key changes needed:**

### 1. Disable request size limits

```csharp
// Program.cs
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
{
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});
```

### 2. Stream to disk with `MultipartReader`

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    if (!request.HasFormContentType ||
        !MediaTypeHeaderValue.TryParse(request.ContentType, out var mt) ||
        string.IsNullOrEmpty(mt.Boundary.Value))
    {
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart request.");
    }

    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(mt.Boundary).Value!;
    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(
                section.ContentDisposition, out var cd) ||
            !cd.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            continue; // skip non-file fields
        }

        var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // never trust client name
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

        await using var stream = File.Create(savePath);
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(stream);       // streams in chunks
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete.");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```

### 3. Disable `IFormFile` model-binding buffering

```csharp
// Add attribute or filter so the framework doesn't try to buffer
app.MapPost("/upload", ...).DisableAntiforgery()
   .WithMetadata(new DisableRequestSizeLimitAttribute());
```

**Why this works:**

| Approach | Memory use for 2 GB file |
|---|---|
| `IFormFile` | **~2 GB** (buffered in RAM) |
| `MultipartReader` | **~80 KB** (`CopyToAsync` uses a small buffer) |

**Other things to wire up:**
- Create the upload directory on startup (`Directory.CreateDirectory`).
- Set `MultipartReader.BodyLengthLimit` if you want per-section caps.
- For reverse-proxy setups (Nginx/IIS), also raise `client_max_body_size` / `maxAllowedContentLength` there.
